<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15070f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15070f">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15070f"> 70(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> unwrought stones / gist charites / grace givers</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">At Phar&aelig;, close to the image of Hermes, Pausanias goes on to tell us, stood about thirty square stones; these the people of Phar&aelig; revered &ldquo;giving to each stone the name of a god.&rdquo; And says Pausanias: &ldquo;in the olden time all the Greeks worshipped <mark>unwrought stones</mark> instead of images.&rdquo; At Thespi&aelig; he elsewhere (IX.27.1) notes the most ancient image of Eros, the winged love-god, was &ldquo;an unwrought stone.&rdquo; In B&oelig;otia, where was a very ancient sanctuary of the <mark>Charites or Grace-Givers</mark>, their images were stones that had fallen from heaven. <small> J.E. Harrison, <a name="MYTH1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MYTH1"><cite title="source">Mythology</cite></a> (1924) 6-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15246f" href="c15all.htm#c15246f">VI.C.15:246(f)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
